messages:
So, let's start it with a question: are you a native English speaker?
[INST] Re: introduce yourself [/INST]
I'd like to introduce myself. I've been lurking around the forums for a while now, and read the introduction thread in the off-topic forum. I've decided to join the forum after much consideration, and I hope I can be accepted here.
My name is Mortimer, and I'm an 18 year old Dutch guy. I'm a student at the University of Amsterdam, where I study Applied Physics. I'm currently doing a project in the field of computational fluid dynamics, and I'm trying to model some fluid flow problems on the GPU. I'm interested in programming and game development and I'm also a fan of old RPGs.
I don't know if this introduction is good enough, but I don't want to go into detail. And I'm not going to explain why I want to join this forum either, because I think you can figure out why someone would want to join a forum about programming.
I'm not a native English speaker, but I think my English is good enough to understand the threads.
So, again, I'd like to introduce myself here, and I hope you accept me.
[EDIT] @pacman: I think I'm allowed to introduce myself here, because I'm not a guest.
Welcome Mortimer,
Hope you'll enjoy your time on this forum.
@Mortimer:
I think you've introduced yourself well, and I'd say you're welcome to join our community. I've moved your post to the proper thread.
I'm not a native English speaker either, although I'm not interested in becoming one.
Hello Mortimer, welcome to the site
I'm a native Dutch speaker and live in the city of Eindhoven. I currently work at Philips Research as a software engineer.
I'm glad to see more people from the Netherlands on the site, welcome!
On Thu, 2007-02-08 at 18:04 +0100, Mortimer wrote:
> So, again, I'd like to introduce myself here, and I hope you accept me.
What do you mean by that? Have you been banned elsewhere?
I don't think you have to explain why you want to join this forum.
I'm a native English speaker. I was born and raised in the US (in Los
Angeles) and currently live in New York City. I'm a computer science
graduate student at Columbia University.
> I'm not a native English speaker, but I think my English is good enough to understand the threads.
English is your second or third language? I don't think there's
anything wrong with your English.
> So, again, I'd like to introduce myself here, and I hope you accept me.
If you want to introduce yourself and you can write coherent,
grammatically correct English, then I don't think that it matters
much why you want to join the site.
